<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE: PAPONE TO RETIRE FROM AMERICAN EXPRESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Aldo Papone, chairman of American Express Travel Related Services Co., a unit 
of American Express Co., will retire Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
Papone will be succeeded by two co-chairmen, Edwin M. Cooperman, president of 
the unit's North American division, and G. Richard Thoman, president of 
American Express International, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
The two men also will serve as co-chief executives of the unit. 
</P>
<P>
Papone, who has held his post since April, 1989, will become a senior adviser 
to American Express Co., reporting to Chairman James D. Robinson III. Papone 
also will continue as a director of the parent company. 
</P>
<P>
"This completes a management evolution that began almost 18 months ago when 
Aldo advised me that he would need to be less active in TRS (Travel Related 
Services) management activities for medical reasons," Robinson said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
Cooperman, an 18-year American Express veteran, is credited with increasing the 
growth of the American Express card. Thoman, an American Express executive 
since 1979, is in charge of the company's traveler's check business and its 
travel services operations outside North America, among other duties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
