<HEADLINE>
<P>
BANK OF BOSTON TO CUT 1,500 JOBS, SEES LOSS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BOSTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Signaling further problems in the banking business, Bank of Boston Corp. said 
Thursday that it will eliminate 1,500 jobs, report a loss of up to $250 million 
for the third quarter and slash its dividend. 
</P>
<P>
The owner of the First National Bank of Boston, the largest bank in New England 
and the nation's 15th-biggest, also said it will take cost-cutting steps aimed 
at saving $100 million by 1991's third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
Like many of its rivals, Bank of Boston attributed its woes to the 
deteriorating real estate market and the ailing economy. 
</P>
<P>
"We are taking decisive and admittedly painful actions," Bank of Boston 
Chairman and Chief Executive Ira Stepanian said. "Yet, in doing so, we are 
building upon an already strong foundation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
