<P>
ISRAELIS BRACE FOR YOM KIPPUR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JERUSALEM 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Israeli forces went on increased alert today as the country started to close 
down for Yom Kippur, Judaism's holiest day. 
</P>
<P>
Motor traffic, radio and television broadcasts and all work will cease for 25 
hours starting tonight, and the rare motorist who ventures onto the roads risks 
being stoned. 
</P>
<P>
Rabbis repeated an annual appeal to Jews not to harm ambulances or security 
forces traveling on the sacred day. 
</P>
<P>
Israel is haunted by a 1973 surprise attack by Arab armies on Yom Kippur as the 
Jews fasted and prayed. Nearly 2,700 Israeli soldiers died in the war, and the 
armed forces have since gone on alert every year, a military spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
Yom Kippur, the day of atonement, is the most solemn day in the Hebrew 
calendar. Many otherwise secular Jews fast from sunset Friday until an hour 
after sunset Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
